The gun does have a safety that was presumably installed by the Zastava factory, but as with most of the Yugo Tokarev imports, it's not very good. title: For Sale/Trade:  1924 COLT "Transition" 1911 .45 Rare, 1 of 4999 Produced
postcontent: This a guns collectors dream come true, and is priced to sell.  If you are not familuar with colt firearms, 1924 - 1938 was known as the "Transition" period.  Colt didn't have a contract with the military to produce the 1911 yet, so they produced 10,000 blued military edition pistols, and 4,999 nickle plated ones.  They were produced in 1924, and they were known as the "transition" gun.  These sell on online auctions from 5,750 - 10,000, and this one is in amazing condition for its age.  The only modification done to this gun was done by colt where they changed out the firing pin for a stainless version.  It has the original hand grips, and while many say there were nicle plate transitions produced, do your research.  This is a very RARE gun to see up for sale, and at this price it should sell quickly.

title: For Sale:  Vietnam 105mm Howitzer  artillery shell, complete, in tube and crate.
location: South of Atlanta, Georgia, United States
postcontent: Item Description: 105mm howitzer M1 HE projectile, case, fuze, fiber shipping container, and wooden crate. Projectile: good condition, dated 1968. Believed to be original paint. Copper rotating band has a demill chisel mark, and is in good condition otherwise. 1968 dated are sought after by collectors. Case: the lacquered steel spiral wrap M14B4 that was prevalent, not brass. 1974(75?) dated. 90 percent of the casings during Vietnam were the spiral wrap- historically correct. Case is dinged up alittle at the mouth at the demill ( see pictures, the one with the rotating band chisel mark) and has been fired.For display purposes, the projectile fits fine in the shell, it displays well with the demilled band facing rear. Very minor surface rust in spots,no dents, overall OK condition, hard to find these war dated as they rusted out years ago. Fuze: an M78 CP ( concrete piercing, bunker buster) dated 1945. Red legs from Vietnam have told me they had used WW2 dated fuzes, and cases early on-historically correct. Black fiber PA74 shipping tube: dated 1974, these are very, very hard to find. The projo and case fit nicely in the tube. Crate: wooden crate is not Vietnam era, but the LOT number ( KN-900-2B) is very close to the tube number ( KN-815-45). Size: wooden crate is 38"x12". All in all, THE perfect gun room addition, this one has sat opened, up against my loading room wall for years, the real deal...time to move it along. Complete 105mm sets like these have long ago disappeared. Note: I will ship, however, I estimate it to be just under 100 lbs.

title: For Sale:  1924 COLT "Transition" 1911 .45 Rare, 1 of 4999 Produced
location: N Myrtle, Myrtle Beach, South Carolina
postcontent: This a guns collectors dream come true, and is priced to sell.  If you are not familuar with colt firearms, 1924 - 1938 was known as the "Transition" period.  Colt didn't have a contract with the military to produce the 1911 yet, so they produced 10,000 blued military edition pistols, and 4,999 nickle plated ones.  They were produced in 1924, and they were known as the "transition" gun.  These sell on online auctions from 5,750 - 10,000, and this one is in amazing condition for its age.  The only modification done to this gun was done by colt where they changed out the firing pin for a stainless version.  It has the original hand grips, and while many say there were nicle plate transitions produced, do your research.  This is a very RARE gun to see up for sale, and at this price it should sell quickly.
